etymologies: late Middle English. As noun from post-classical Latin ambidexter corrupt lawyer (or occasionally juror) who takes fees or bribes from both sides in a case, use as noun of ambidexter

definitions: A person who has two contradictory or incompatible roles; a double-dealer; a deceitful or hypocritical person.
A corrupt lawyer (or occasionally juror) who takes fees or bribes from both sides in a case.
A person who is able to use the right and left hands equally well; an ambidextrous person.
Double-dealing, deceitful, hypocritical; specifically (of a juror or lawyer) that corruptly takes fees or bribes from both sides in a legal case.
